Deep learning model for predicting phase diagrams of block copolymers
Takeshi Aoyagi
Research Center for Computational Design of Advanced Functional Materials, National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology (AIST), Central 2, 1-1-1 Umezono, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-8568, Japan
ARTICLE INFO
Keywords:
Block copolymer Micro phase separation Deep learning Convolutional neural network
ABSTRACT
Block copolymers show various microphase-separated structures depending on their chain architecture and the interaction parameters between the different chemical structures of monomeric unit χ. Self-consistent field theory is a powerful tool to predict such phase-separated structures, and phase diagrams of block copolymers have been reported using self-consistent field theory. However, obtaining stable morphology of each polymer structure and the χ parameter requires intensive computational study. We applied deep learning to predict phase diagrams from metastable structures obtained by crude, cost-effective self-consistent field calculation. We used a 3D convolutional neural network for classification of the metastable structures, and a limited number of sets of block copolymer structures and χ parameters with stable phase labels were used for training. After the model was trained using the training set, it successfully assigned the metastable structures of a wide variety of diblock and triblock copolymers to the correct stable phases. This approach is capable of predicting the phase diagrams of block copolymers effectively without intensive self-consistent field calculation.
1. Introduction
Block copolymers consist of multiple sub-chains with different chemical structures, and the sub-chains are connected by chemical bonds. Block copolymers have many topological shapes, such as linear, star, and comb-like chains. When the chain length of each block is long enough and the attractive interactions between different chemical structures are weak, these blocks are not miscible and show a multiphase structure. However, the immiscible blocks are connected by chemical bonds; thus, the size of the phase-separated domains is restricted to the order of magnitude of the chain length. That type of phase separation is known as microphase separation. Several typical morphologies of microphase separation of block copolymers have been observed, such as body center cubic sphere (S in figures), hexagonal cylinder (C), double gyroid (G), and lamellar (L) structure. When different blocks are miscible, the homogenous disorder state (D) can be observed in addition to phase-separated morphology. Such morphologies depend on chain length, the volume fraction of each block, and the interaction parameter χ between different blocks. The χ parameter corresponds to the miscibility between different chemical structures in each block chain, and larger values of χ mean less miscibility. The parameter χ multiplied by the number of segments in a chain N, expressed as χN, is a miscibility criterion in polymer chains. The phase diagrams for typical block copolymers are well studied by
both theoretical calculations [1–6] and experiments [7–9]. Selfconsistent field theory (SCFT) is a powerful method to predict the microphase-separated structure of block copolymers [10–12]. SCFT applies topological information about polymer chains by solving the Edwards equation [10], and the system’s free energy consists of a configurational entropic part and an enthalpic part calculated on the basis of the interactions between different chemical structures. Stable morphology can be determined by comparing the free energy of various morphologies, and intensive calculations are needed to obtain the precise free energy of each morphology, including unit cell size optimization of the periodic structure. This process requires much computational cost. If we skip this rigorous step, we cannot obtain the most stable structure, and many metastable structures are observed. Although there should be structural similarity between the stable morphology and metastable structures, it is currently difficult to assign stable morphology from such metastable structures by numerical analysis of the metastable structures. Recently, machine learning has been widely used in materials science, including application to polymeric materials [13–22]. The training sets have included atomistic-level molecular and crystalline structures and higher-order structures such as heterogeneous-phase polymer blends and polymer–filler composites. The convolutional neural network (CNN) [23] is a widely employed method of 2D image recognition [24–26]. CNN methods can be extended to 3D images (3DCNN),
