and 3DCNN was applied for the investigation of structure–property relationships of composite materials [27,28]. Yang [27] produced the microstructures of a two-component composite with contrasting physical properties such as stiffness. Then, a 3DCNN was trained with information about the structure and stiffness of composites obtained by finite element analysis. Although that approach succeeded in predicting properties from microstructure, those microstructures were obtained using a statistical approach [29] with no physical background. We applied such an approach to classify metastable structures obtained by SCFT calculation based on a well-established physical background. The objective of image recognition of metastable structures obtained by SCFT calculation of block copolymers is to predict the copolymers’ stable morphologies from their metastable structures by associating the metastable structures with stable phase labels. If that association is accurate, the model should be able to predict copolymers’ stable morphologies on the basis of their corresponding metastable structures from crude, inexpensive SCFT calculation.
2. Polymer samples and SCFT calculation
We focused on block copolymer structures, which are well studied by precise SCFT calculation. AB-type block copolymers are the system with the most-studied phase diagrams. Matsen published an excellent review on studies of phase diagrams of AB-type block copolymers [2]. The training sets have primarily consisted of phase diagrams of AB diblock copolymers. However, we noticed that the phase diagrams of diblock copolymers were symmetrically shaped in a pattern that varied according to their volume fractions, and the volume fractions could be the main descriptor in the model to find the stable morphology. Thus, in addition to the diblock copolymers, we used AB2 star block copolymers in our training set. The reason of the choice of the AB2 star block copolymers is that the structure is simple in brunched polymers and the phase diagram are well studied [2]. Fig. 1 shows the sets of volume fractions and χN values used in the training set. As little selection as possible was performed on those conditions so that all phases would be included and critical phase boundaries could be clarified. As AB diblock copolymers have symmetric distributions of the A and B blocks, only the A segment-minor region (fA ≤ 0.5) was used as an AB diblock copolymer, while the A segment-rich region was considered as an AB2 star block copolymer. Although phase-space SCFT calculations are often conducted to predict highly symmetric stable-phase structures, we conducted realspace SCFT calculations to obtain metastable structures that had little symmetry and would have been difficult to obtain by phase-space
calculation. The SUSHI package [30], a component of the OCTA system [31,32], was used for the real-space SCFT calculation. In the realspace SCFT calculation, the statistical weight of a chain is obtained by solving the following Edwards equation:
∂
∂tQK (i, r) =
[b2
6 ∇2 VK (r)
]
QK (i, r) (1)
where QK(i,r) is the path integral describing the equilibrium statistical weight of the ith segment of segment type K located at r, b is the Kuhn statistical length, and VK is the self-consistent field, which is determined by the incompressible condition and the interaction between segments. The details of the implementation in SUSHI can be found in the references [30,32]. In the SUSHI implementation, the chain length was defined as Nb. N was set to 20 and 40 for each point, and the length of the A block and the χ parameter were determined by the corresponding volume fraction and χN in the phase diagram, respectively. The system size was set as a 32 × 32 × 32[b] cubic cell with periodic boundary conditions. We obtained 100–200 structures at each point and chain length by beginning the calculation from a homogenous state and adding different random initial noise during each iteration. We confirmed the free energy converged after the iteration of SCFT calculation (typically 20,000 iterations). Thus, we concluded that the obtained structures were metastable structures and not unstable ones. We should note that these structures were obtained by spinodal decomposition from homogenous state and the phase boundary could be slightly different from binodal phase boundary by conducting rigorous minimization of free energy. Fig. 2 shows examples of the metastable structures for each stable phase. In total, 3000 metastable structures were used for training of the 3DCNN. Test dataset was taken from the full range of phase diagrams of AB diblock copolymers and AB2 star block copolymers with volume fractions of the A segment ranging 0.05–0.50 and 0.05–0.95, respectively (χN ranged 10–40 for both copolymer types). In addition to the copolymer types used for training, ABA asymmetric triblock copolymers were included in the test dataset, because they are the simplest structure in asymmetric multiblock copolymers. The phase diagrams of asymmetric triblock copolymers were also studied by Matsen [3]. The phase boundary changed in terms of asymmetricity, which was defined as τ in ref. [3]. Three sets of metastable structures for each set of polymer structure and χN were obtained by SCFT calculation to predict the stable phase.
Fig. 1. Plot of volume fractions and χN values used for training set. (a) AB diblock copolymer, (b) AB2 star block copolymer. Each plot is colored depending on phase: S (blue), C (green), G (red), L (yellow), and D (black). Background phase diagrams are adapted from Fig. 1 and Fig. 5 in ref. [2] with permission. Copyright 2012 American Chemical Society.
