3. Deep learning method
Fig. 3 shows the 3DCNN architecture used in this study. The inputs were sets of volume fractions of each segment type in each 32 × 32 × 32 grid voxel (obtained from SCFT calculation) and a one-hot vector of the five types of stable phase labels for the corresponding set of polymer structures and χN values. We neglected to include the O70, Ssp, and SA15 phases in the precise phase diagrams because the region of the O70 phase is very narrow, and the Ssp and SA15 phases are difficult to separate from the S phase. Four convolutional layers and two max-pooling layers were followed by flatten and dense layers. A ReLU function [33] was used for activation of each layer except the last one. A softmax function [34] was used for the activation of last layer to output the probabilities of the five phases. Dropout with a 0.4 drop rate was applied after each of the two max pooling layers and the first dense layer to avoid overfitting. To increase accuracy of prediction in machine learning, it is desirable to use as large of a dataset as possible. Thus, we increased the number of training data by exchanging the axes of the calculated volume fraction data, i.e., (x,y,z) data were changed to (z,x,y), (y,z,x), (z,y,x), (y,x,z), and (x,z,y). These exchanges performed a six-fold augmentation on the number of data. In addition, the volume fraction of segment B was used in addition to that of segment A, as both volume fractions should result in the same isosurface. This operation doubled the total number of data. The above processes increased the number of data from 3000 to 36,000. The 3DCNN was implemented using Tensorflow 2.1.0 [35]. We assigned 80% and 20% of the all training dataset as the training and validation sets, respectively. The Adam optimizer [36] was used to associate the volume fraction data with the categorized stable phase
labels. Categorical cross-entropy [37] was used as the loss function, and the batch size was set to 32. After 1000 epochs, the loss and accuracy
were 8 × 10 7 and 1.000 for trained data and 0.0066 and 0.9982 for validation data, respectively. This result indicated good training accuracy, and the accuracy for validation data was good enough although a little overfitting was observed. Stable phases were predicted for the test dataset using the trained 3DCNN network. The output of the 3DCNN is an array of probabilities of five phases. Three metastable structures obtained from different initial noise distributions and the volume fractions of both the A and B segments were used for input. As a result, a total of six probability arrays were summed, and the predicted phase was determined from the maximum probability in the summed array.
4. Results and discussion
Fig. 4 shows the predicted phase diagram of AB diblock copolymers. The results of chain length N = 20 and 40 are shown in Fig. 4(a) and (b) by scaling χN. The original phase diagram obtained from intensive SCFT calculation was mostly reproduced, even in the region where no samples were used for training. Fig. 5 shows the predicted phase diagram of AB2 star block copolymers. N is the number of segments of the entire molecule. Since the chain structure of AB2 star block copolymers is not symmetric for the volume fraction, the SCFT also gives unsymmetrical phase diagram. Although the agreement with the original SCFT phase diagram was relatively poor compared with the AB diblock case, asymmetricity was reproduced well, and the boundary was close to that of the original
Fig. 2. Examples of metastable structures for each stable phase. Stable structures are shown on top, and four metastable structures are shown below for each stable phase. Isosurfaces of the 0.5 volume fraction of A block are shown.
Fig. 3. 3DCNN architecture used for this study.
