phase diagram. The results imply that the asymmetricity of the phase diagram can be reproduced by training with a small number of AB2 samples and a large number of diblock samples that show symmetric phase diagrams. Thus, as expected, the 3DCNN training set could account for not only the volume fraction but also structure while classifying the stable phase. Fig. 6 shows the predicted phase diagram of ABA asymmetric triblock copolymers. Asymmetricity τ is an additional parameter and asymmetricity of phase diagram also depend on the parameter. The vertical axis is shown in units of τ, and the results for different χN values are shown in different figures in the style of Fig. 3 in ref. [3]. N is the number of segments of the entire molecule. The predicted phase diagrams reproduce the original SCFT results well. The predicted phase diagram shows a wider disorder phase than seen in the original SCFT results, especially in the case of χN = 20. At χN = 20 and larger τ values, there is a quasi-stable region where nucleation is a driving force for phase separation, and no spinodal decomposition is observed. SCFT calculation from the homogenous state cannot reproduce nucleation
while staying in the homogenous (disordered) state. We examined some metastable structures for which the predicted phases were correct and incorrect. Fig. 7 shows examples of metastable structures of ABA asymmetric triblock copolymers. Although the regions depicted in both Fig. 7(a) and (b) were in the lamellar phase according to precise SCFT calculation, the 3DCNN predicted that the region in Fig. 7 (b) was in the cylinder phase. Observation by human eye would also lead to assigning Fig. 7(b) a cylinder-like structure. Thus, the 3DCNN seems to recognize the structure and classify the stable phase correctly in this case. Fig. 8 shows examples of metastable structures of AB2 star block copolymers. Although Fig. 8(a) is in the sphere phase, and Fig. 8(b) is in the cylinder phase, the predicted results were cylinder phase in both cases. Fig. 8(a) clearly shows a spherical structure. Thus, the 3DCNN could not recognize structure correctly in this case. One possible explanation for this failure is that number of training data for the spherical phase was too small. Further refinement of the deep learning network and quantitative analysis of those structures should be conducted in the future.
5. Conclusion
We conducted a deep learning study to classify the microphaseseparated structures of block copolymers. We applied the 3DCNN architecture to classify 3D phase-separated structure. The metastable structures of sets of polymer structures and χN values were obtained by crude, inexpensive SCFT calculation. The training set information included the correspondence between volume fractions of segment types and structures and the stable phase labels obtained by intensive, rigorous SCFT calculation. The 3DCNN network trained by a limited number of sets of polymer structures and χN values successfully reproduced the phase diagrams of a wide variety of copolymer types: AB diblock, AB2 star, and ABA asymmetric triblock copolymers. Using predicted stable morphology as an initial guess, the precise SCFT can be conducted. This approach will reduce the total computational cost of SCFT to determine the stable morphology by reducing candidates to be considered. This study’s results can be applied to various kinds of polymers, and this technique could enable the prediction of phase diagrams of unknown polymer structures by conducting cost-effective calculations without intensive SCFT calculations. Furthermore, this approach combining crude computational simulation and image recognition by deep learning indicates a potential to be applied in general to accelerate computational simulation for predicting
